This book is a must-read for understanding the dangers of online communities. It focuses on the incel community and misogyny, which isn’t just a few guys on the internet, but an underground phenomenon that connects groups of men from around the world together in a way that has never been possible before. It showcases the very real link between extremist fringe thoughts and institutionalised abuses of power, and tracks a worrying connection between incel speak and the actions of our political leaders, not to mention the behavior of our neighbors in our everyday lives. It shows how abuse becomes normalized, celebrated and rewarded. But the thing that got me the most was how much this book felt like it could be about mobilised antisemitism. I have been banging the drum for years that we spend too much time divided by our fears and our differences but if we don’t learn from other terrorised online communities then we’re alone fighting the same battles with even fewer resources and allies. The Brett Kavanaugh moment wasn’t just a moment for women and misogyny; it was a green light for online terrorism. Twitter is not an experiment owned by a tech darling / jokester (depending on which camp you fall in), it’s a tool for empowering destructive mindsets, criminal action and hate speech. The only answer in my opinion is legislation but we would do well to start having this conversation across divides because the people with the power aren’t interested in policing themselves or protecting the lives of those being targeted. 📚

Today marks the 50th anniversary of a genre that changed the world: Hip-hop. Ten years ago I was panicking in an office at the weekend because a cover star had fallen thru and I did some research and realised it was 40 years since the first block party in New York. Somehow within 48 hours I’d managed to track down Kool Herc, Afrika Bambaataa, the living members of Run DMC and Steven Tyler, plus Debbie Harry, Cypress Hill, Spinderella, Snoop Dogg, RZA and so many more and put together an issue of NME to tell the story of how it all began. Still so proud to this day and can’t believe I used to get to do cool shit like this.

Day 1 in eretz Israel. I have a lot to process and a lot to say and it will come in due course. Being here right now is like being reborn from the rubble. Today I visited the devastation at kibbutz Be’eri and the site of the Nova music festival with a survivor returning for his first time. His name is Nehori; a beautiful soul. Brave. True bravery. I cannot describe the twin feelings of being a Jew in Israel, able to joyously exhale upon arrival after holding my breath since October 7, while also having my heart break even more deeply while understanding that the evil this country was built to bury has come back worse than ever. Non-Jewish people can’t understand but can and should display compassion. Those who don’t display compassion simply view Jews as subhuman and they say as much by name-calling, gaslighting and denying. Denying our right to exist, our right to be free in our homeland, our right to be safe. It’s very cool to be those people but it’s vile. It’s evil. Bearing witness to the atrocities of Hamas at this point in time is the most important thing I have ever done with my life. Because it’s now or never. Make no mistake about Hamas. They are Nazis. They came to hunt Jews. The things I saw today should have been kept in the Holocaust museums. Instead they were brought back to life. Kids running for their lives through open fields and forests. Survivors starving and splitting an orange between twelve. Hebrew books torn and burned down with houses. Jews trapped in concrete shelters and dealt with by RPGs until their bodies were beyond recognition. These are the new Nazis. And they must be destroyed. (Much much more to come from me, but for now a much-needed “lila tov”). 🇮🇱

I am deeply grateful to Guy and Eve for taking the time to bear witness, to hear my story, and help keep the memories of my beautiful friends alive. They were beautiful people. We came here to dance, to have fun, to laugh. I miss them every day.

It is not easy to return to the place it happened. The place where I survived, but my friends took their last breaths. I believe I survived for a reason, and I believe I have a duty to use my voice to tell the world the truth, to speak out against lies and injustice, and to fight for humanity, love and peace. These were the principles my friends lived by. I will keep their legacy alive. 🇮🇱
